Text: I'm a homeless single mom to two chronically sick kids in the US.  Before becoming homeless, I had a decent-pay accounting job & still couldn't afford our medical care.  Prescriptions, insurance, co-pays, deductibles, specialists, tests, hospital are all trigger words to me now.

Embedded_text:
And then there's how America has historically treated mental health as an afterthought instead of a priority,  stigmatized those seeking help, & made it so expensive that it's a privilege to afford...
So, when you ask what you can do to help, my answer is: help break the stigma.

Capitalist greed in America also has the real estate market making rent unaffordable, the banks and creditors penalizing struggling accounts with exorbitant interest, fees, and fines making it exponentially harder to get out of the red...

I watched your video & hope you choose to highlight a variety of people, not just ones who perpetuate negative stigmas.  We need to break those stigmas.   Some homeless people have never done drugs, have never been in trouble with the law, and are homeless because... (a thread)

Text: That's only one of many manipulation tactics pharmaceutical companies use.  They promise relief from depression & anxiety but fail to mention (or mention quietly) how you'll be too tired to stay awake, battle terrible side effects, & lose your joy, too.  Mindfulness has helped.

What You Can Never Change:

1. The past
2. The world
3. Other people

What You Can Always Change:

1. Your attitude
2. Your assumptions
3. Your beliefs
